<font color="#FF0000">A REVIEW</font><br>
<tt>Sat Sep 27 18:19:10 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Kali Tal's web site, a review:<br><br>
I just did a covert recon on Kali Tal's sixties project. I hope I didn't leave any digital cookies behind. The site was as I last saw it last year, a monument to self proclaimed revisionism and a rewrite of history. The focus continues on the odd splinters of society cast in ways that give the appearance of socially significant import. I do not think that any of it is really recognizable to most people &quot;of the 60's&quot; except those in charge of the project whose obvious caste system excludes even the most liberal critic. In the 60's, if any of this stuff hit small town middle class America, it would have been stomped upon and soundly thrashed. The values espoused by the proprietors of the site have little in common with the realities of life, except for those who like to hear themselves whine. Whining seems to be the way one's work is admitted to this show. Obscurity of content is another thankfull attribute. The followers of Hale-Bopp had more of a grounded thesis than the fossilized display of worn out cliche ridden so-called literature.<br><br>
The topics of the Vietnam War and Vietnam Veterans is treated as if Uncle Ho himself had been on the editorial board. I have not seen such a compendium of hearsay whining and contempt since Jane Fonda strutted her stuff and gave the enemy a morale boost at our expense.<br><br>
Taken in total, the site has content destined to languish upon the refuse pile of obscurity, and will eventually kindle the spontaneous smoldering combustion of its own demise. <br><br>
Your Covert Critic,<br><br>
DZ
